result.judgement: Prediction correctly lists the names of customers whose IDs are absent from Orders, matching the question’s requirement; no unjustified filters are added.

Predicted query properly lists status, invoice date, and (possibly null) shipment date for every invoice, matching a plain reading of “all invoices,” whereas the gold omits invoices without shipments.
Predicted query correctly returns order_id, status, and product count for every order using a proper join and grouping; differences from gold are immaterial.

Prediction joins Shipments by order_id, so it pairs every item of an order with every shipment of that order, including items not actually shipped and possibly wrong dates, whereas the gold query uses Shipment_Items to link items that truly belong to each shipment; thus prediction over-includes and gives wrong product-date pairs.

Predicted query only requires an order to have a shipment and can therefore list products whose specific order items were never included in any shipment, whereas the gold query correctly uses Shipment_Items to ensure the exact items were shipped; the prediction thus violates the question’s anchor.

Prediction joins Shipments only on order_id, so any item in an order that has at least one shipped item is returned; it does not verify that the specific order item itself appears in Shipment_Items, thus over-includes unshipped items. Gold correctly joins through Shipment_Items.
Prediction returns order id, status, and item count per order exactly as asked; column order difference is harmless.
Predicted query correctly lists customers with no orders and returns the requested name fields; column order differences are immaterial.

Predicted query joins Shipments to Orders but skips Shipment_Items, so it can return order items that were never included in any shipment; therefore it does not reliably answer which products have actually been shipped, unlike the gold.
Prediction reasonably lists every invoice with its status, invoice date, and (if present) shipment date, matching a plain reading of “for all invoices.”
Prediction joins shipments only by order, so it wrongly returns items that may not be in the shipment (e.g., “Out of Stock”), violating the item-level shipped requirement.
Predicted query joins shipments to order_items only via order_id, ignoring Shipment_Items, so it can label un-shipped products as shipped; gold follows correct linkage, thus pred is wrong.

Predicted query joins by order_id and therefore includes items that belong to shipped orders even if the specific order item lacks a record in Shipment_Items, so it returns extra rows not guaranteed to be shipped.
Predicted query returns each order’s id, status, and the count of its products, matching the question requirements.
